Excellent contribution from everyone! This is a great venue to share our institutions&#39; current practice with Semaglutide.&#160;
At the University Health Network, we ask patients who use Semaglutide for weight loss to stop three weeks before surgery. For diabetes, we ask the patient to stop one week before surgery. I have also attached our pre-operative guide for Semaglutide.
I want to add to Janey’s post that the pH and volume of gastric contents can affect the aspiration severity level. Aspiration of a gastric fluid volume &gt; 25 mL with a pH &lt; 2.5 will cause pulmonary injury. In addition to rapid-sequence induction, we can give oral antacids or histamine-2-receptor antagonists as preventive measures. Oral antacids like sodium citrate can be given 15 – 30 minutes before the induction of anesthesia. It effectively neutralizes stomach acid, reducing the risk of aspiration pneumonitis. Histamine-2-receptor antagonists reduce gastric acid secretion by blocking the ability of histamine to induce acidic secretion. However, they do not reliably affect gastric fluid volume or gastric-emptying time.&#160;
Even with all the preventive measures, if aspiration occurs and gastric contents are noted in the pharynx, the head should immediately be displaced laterally, the pharynx cleared by suction, and the patient should be intubated if pharyngeal reflexes are absent. Also, the head-down position will facilitate the removal of secretions and prevent gastric contents from tracking down the trachea from the pharynx by gravity. Patients should then be observed for 24 to 48 hours for aspiration pneumonitis.&#160;

Excellent discussion!&#160;
All of you have brought different important aspects of postoperative pain management. Multimodal analgesia is the way to go, where we use a combination of different medications and techniques to target various pain pathways and mechanisms so that we can provide more effective pain relief while minimizing the side effects associated with high doses of a single medication.
As Janey and Renee pointed out, multimodal analgesia is not limited to postoperatively but is incorporated throughout the preoperative, intraoperative, and postoperative phases. Furthermore, especially with the opioid epidemic, we are looking into other medications to reduce opioid consumption while enhancing pain control and improving overall patient outcomes. Other medications include non-opioid analgesics, local anesthetics, Ketamine, and adjuvant medications such as Gabapentinoids, antidepressants, anxiolytics, and muscle relaxants. Even non-medicinal approaches can play a role, such as music therapy, meditation, and acupuncture, to name a few.

Hi Kurt,&#160;
Having started working in the OR in the past month, one of the areas I work a lot in is the regional block room. This is new for me and I&#39;ve done a lot of learning about it. Your chart is a great way to compare and contrast the pros and cons of each method of anesthesia.&#160; It seems to me that regional anesthesia (RA) is a sort of up and coming type of anesthesia that is rapidly changing and expanding, with some centers doing huge amounts of them while others less so.&#160; One of the main advantages to the use of RA is the significant reduction in need for opioids post operatively. Patients with high risk factors of opioid related complications like patients with high BMI, OSA, elderly benefit greatly.&#160;
To comment on your question Laryssa, anecdotally in the past few weeks, I&#39;ve seen a large number of nerve blocks and spinal anesthetics administered. At my institution, the typical patient will receive midazolam prior to the nerve block/spinal to help ease the anxiety of the procedure, which seems to work very well.&#160; On the odd occasion we&#39;ve had patients refuse nerve blocks while awake, and they&#39;ve been done after induction as the benefit of post operative pain control and reduced need for opioids is so high in some patients.

As pointed out by April, the usage of barbiturates in anesthesia has dramatically declined. The only usage in anesthesia nowadays is in electroconvulsive therapy (ECT), which involves inducing seizures. Methohexital is the preferred agent in ECT because it lowers the seizure threshold and has a longer seizure duration than other intravenous anesthetics such as Propofol. &#160;&#160;
Previously, the barbiturate of choice was Thiopental because of its quick onset as an induction agent and neuroprotection properties. Thiopental is a potent vasoconstrictor, which decreases cerebral blood flow, cerebral blood volume, and cerebral metabolic oxygen requirements. It can be used to initiate barbiturate comas, which have been used in patients with ischemic neurological deficits due to cerebral vasospasm after subarachnoid hemorrhage. Also, Thiopental used to be the gold standard agent for rapid sequence induction.&#160;
However, with the introduction of non-barbiturates such as Propofol and Ketamine, Thiopental lost its popularity. &#160;In addition to its inadequacy in suppressing airway reflexes during airway manipulation, another major disadvantage of Thiopental is its long half-life and prolonged recovery period due to the retention of drugs by fat tissues. It also induces histamine release. In addition, Thiopental has no analgesic properties when compared to Ketamine.
In fact, Thiopental has no longer been manufactured since 2011 due to the public becoming aware of its use in capital punishment (application of lethal injection in the death penalty), which led to the sole manufacturer, Hospira, stopping the production of the drug.

Great contribution, everyone!
Renee has nicely reminded us that the synergism between a benzodiazepine and an opioid not only potentiates their therapeutic effects, but also their side effects.&#160;
The advantage of synergism is that we can now use a lower dose of each drug to achieve the same level of effect. &#160;Therefore, toxicity and unwanted side effects are reduced, while still achieving the desired effects. This will also result in a quicker recovery, which is especially important for outpatient sedative procedures. &#160;
I commonly use 0.5 – 2 mg Midazolam and 25 – 50 mcg Fentanyl (and sometimes together with 25 – 50 mg Propofol) for procedural sedation procedures such as cataract removal, corneal transplant, and transesophageal echocardiography (TEE). &#160;The small dosage of opioid in this combination is mainly to enhance the sedative effect of the benzodiazepine as opposed to making use of its analgesic effect. &#160;The procedural pain is usually taken care of by local infiltration or nerve blocks with local anesthetics.
Another sedation cocktail that I know some institutions commonly use is “ketofol,” which combines Ketamine and Propofol. Propofol tends to cause hypotension and bradycardia, whereas ketamine causes hypertension and tachycardia. It seems that the side effects of each drug balance off each other.&#160;
In addition, interactions between various intravenous drugs and inhaled volatiles are synergistic as well. &#160;For example, there is a synergistic effect between narcotics and inhaled volatiles.
