Hi Paula,
Thanks for the overview of local and regional anesthesia. &#160;
It is interesting to note that local anesthetics can produce quite a different intensity of pain blockade, temperature sensation, and motor function. &#160;Nerve fibers have different sensitivities to local anesthetics because of different ion channel compositions or different arrangements of channels within the axon. &#160;We must consider all these factors when picking a local anesthetic and its dosage. &#160;
As you have mentioned, the motor function is usually spared with local doses, such as in a local infiltration. &#160;The dose of local anesthetics will anesthetize the nerve endings in a small area of tissue proximal to the site of the local anesthetic injection. &#160;This usage of local anesthetics is ideal in day surgery patients where ambulation is essential for discharge.
With regional doses, motor function will be profoundly blocked. This is valuable to patients who are contraindicated for general anesthesia. &#160;The required regional doses will depend on the type of regional block, the site of injection, and the local anesthetic used. &#160;For example, both spinal and epidural blocks can produce motor blockade from the waist down. &#160;A spinal block requires a relatively small dose because the local anesthetic is injected directly into the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). &#160;In contrast, using the same local anesthetic, an epidural block will require a larger dose because it is not injected in CSF and needs to diffuse into the subarachnoid space through the dura. &#160;
One last point I want to highlight quickly is the sequence of the clinical blockade. &#160;Complete blockade of peripheral nerves usually progresses in the following order:
1) &#160; &#160;Sympathetic block with peripheral vasodilation<br/>2) &#160; &#160;Loss of pain and temperature sensation<br/>3) &#160; &#160;Loss of proprioception<br/>4) &#160; &#160;Loss of touch and pressure sensation<br/>5) &#160; &#160;Motor paralysis
These are the markers we look for when testing block effectiveness.

