This is a very informative summary from everyone. It is very important to at least put great emphasis on the prevention of LAST. I have noted that these have all been discussed already. My take away from the discussion and my readings. Lipid Emulsion should be on all resuscitation carts with the other emergency drugs. Once there is a suspicion of LAST, especially if patients are presenting with cardiac symptoms, sustained arrhythmias or neurological symptoms like seizures, lipid emulsion should be initiated immediately. As per&#160; the ASRA guidelines, an intravenous bolus dose of 20% lipid emulsion starts with a bolus of 1.5 mL/kg over 2 to 3 minutes (100 mL if greater than 70 kg) followed by a continuous infusion at 0.25 mL/kg/min for 30-60 minutes (this varies from text to text, some literature says 15 to 20 minutes). The bolus dose can be repeated once or twice if there is still cardiac instability and the rate increased to 0.5ml/kg/min. Lipid emulsion infusion should be continued for at least 15 minutes after hemodynamic stability is achieved. Lipid emulsion is quite effective from the onset, however, other supportive measures may need to be initiated or on standby. These include proper airway management, seizure control and cardiovascular support. It is also important to continue to monitor the patient very closely for another 2 hours for signs of recurrent toxicity, as local anesthetics can redistribute overtime.
